1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,420
I want you to try something for me.

2
00:00:01,740 --> 00:00:03,720
I want you to picture an object in your mind.

3
00:00:04,220 --> 00:00:08,500
I'm going to describe it, and you just need to visualize the image I'm painting.

4
00:00:09,300 --> 00:00:09,560
Ready?

5
00:00:10,100 --> 00:00:12,140
It's a small, red, wooden box.

6
00:00:12,380 --> 00:00:13,500
Yeah, very easy to picture.

7
00:00:13,640 --> 00:00:15,580
I mean, the image just snaps right into focus.

8
00:00:15,680 --> 00:00:15,920
Right.

9
00:00:16,500 --> 00:00:17,580
Now, clear that image.

10
00:00:18,180 --> 00:00:19,800
Just shake the mental etch to sketch.

11
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:24,600
I want you to try picturing this object instead, a wooden, red, small box.

12
00:00:24,660 --> 00:00:25,240
Oh, wow.

13
00:00:25,400 --> 00:00:27,560
Yeah, that immediately feels viscerally wrong.

14
00:00:27,640 --> 00:00:29,480
It's actually almost jarring to process.

15
00:00:29,480 --> 00:00:30,800
It really is, right?

16
00:00:30,940 --> 00:00:35,700
It feels like a wrong note played loudly in a very familiar song.

17
00:00:36,580 --> 00:00:43,360
If you're a native English speaker, hearing the phrase, a wooden, red, small box, probably just made your brain itch.

18
00:00:43,420 --> 00:00:43,880
Oh, absolutely.

19
00:00:44,180 --> 00:00:47,780
I know it's completely incorrect, but if I were to ask you to explain exactly why it's wrong,

20
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:51,560
or, you know, ask you to recite the specific grammatical rule you just violated.

21
00:00:51,800 --> 00:00:52,620
You probably couldn't do it.

22
00:00:52,960 --> 00:00:54,140
Exactly, you couldn't.

23
00:00:54,180 --> 00:00:57,560
Which points to a really fascinating reality about human cognition.

24
00:00:57,560 --> 00:01:06,540
I mean, you obey that invisible rule flawlessly every single time you speak, thousands of times a day, without ever consciously accessing it.

25
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:12,540
Yeah, and that weird unconscious grammar rule is actually the starting point for unlocking something massive.

26
00:01:12,880 --> 00:01:14,700
So welcome to this deep dive.

27
00:01:15,060 --> 00:01:20,880
Today, we are unpacking a stack of three incredible papers published in June 2026.

28
00:01:20,980 --> 00:01:22,720
Right, by an independent researcher named Flyxion.

29
00:01:22,720 --> 00:01:24,100
Yes, Flyxion.

30
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:30,160
And what makes these papers so compelling is that on the surface, they seem, well, completely unrelated.

31
00:01:30,420 --> 00:01:34,520
I mean, one is about linguistics, one is about the architecture of artificial intelligence,

32
00:01:34,520 --> 00:01:39,400
and one is about the historical evolution of human written language.

33
00:01:39,560 --> 00:01:41,420
Yeah, they sound totally disconnected.

34
00:01:41,900 --> 00:01:46,840
Yet they're actually tackling the exact same profound question from three different angles.

35
00:01:47,040 --> 00:01:48,480
Which is crazy to think about.

36
00:01:48,480 --> 00:01:49,220
It really is.

37
00:01:49,460 --> 00:01:55,980
They're looking at how intelligent systems, and by that we mean human minds, entire cultural languages, and artificial intelligences,

38
00:01:56,360 --> 00:02:04,440
how they decide which details about the physical world to preserve, and which details to merge together, compress, or just, you know, ignore entirely.

39
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:05,680
Okay, let's unpack this.

40
00:02:06,040 --> 00:02:12,960
Because the core concept, uniting all these sources, basically flips our standard assumption about communication right on its head.

41
00:02:12,960 --> 00:02:18,660
But the papers argue that we do not process information simply to accurately describe the world.

42
00:02:19,200 --> 00:02:20,740
Like, that's just a secondary function.

43
00:02:21,080 --> 00:02:25,800
We process information to navigate the world without crashing into things.

44
00:02:25,960 --> 00:02:31,700
Yeah, the distinction between describing and navigating, it completely changes how we measure intelligence.

45
00:02:32,220 --> 00:02:33,000
How so?

46
00:02:33,180 --> 00:02:34,180
Like, give me an example.

47
00:02:34,180 --> 00:02:40,520
Well, think about a highly detailed topographical map versus, say, a simple subway map.

48
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:44,640
A topographical map perfectly describes the terrain, right?

49
00:02:44,740 --> 00:02:46,880
Every elevation change, every contour.

50
00:02:46,940 --> 00:02:48,300
Right, super accurate.

51
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:48,960
Exactly.

52
00:02:49,300 --> 00:02:54,180
But if you're just trying to get from Times Square to Brooklyn, a topographical map is useless.

53
00:02:54,580 --> 00:02:57,020
You don't need a perfect description of the physical world.

54
00:02:57,120 --> 00:02:58,940
Right, you just need to know which train to get on.

55
00:02:58,940 --> 00:03:04,940
Yes, you need a navigational tool that preserves only the specific distinctions that get you to your destination.

56
00:03:05,240 --> 00:03:11,300
Okay, so to understand this grand theory of navigating reality, we have to start right back where we began a moment ago.

57
00:03:11,620 --> 00:03:16,200
With that weird, unconscious grammar rule inside your head about the wooden box.

58
00:03:16,260 --> 00:03:17,120
The adjective order.

59
00:03:17,520 --> 00:03:20,380
Right, let's look at the actual rule governing this.

60
00:03:21,060 --> 00:03:23,540
Linguists call it the English adjective order constraint.

61
00:03:23,540 --> 00:03:31,760
There is this highly rigid, fixed sequence that multiple adjectives modifying a noun must follow.

62
00:03:31,880 --> 00:03:37,740
Yeah, and the standard sequence, which has been documented by grammarians for decades, follows a very specific path.

63
00:03:37,840 --> 00:03:39,240
And it's long, too.

64
00:03:39,340 --> 00:03:40,400
Oh, it's very long.

65
00:03:40,840 --> 00:03:50,540
It begins with the determiner in quantity, then opinion, size, age, shape, color, origin, material, purpose, and finally the noun itself.

66
00:03:50,540 --> 00:03:55,480
Yeah, I'm looking at a chart from the first paper, and it gives this perfectly absurd sentence to illustrate it.

67
00:03:55,580 --> 00:03:56,220
Listen to this.

68
00:03:57,040 --> 00:04:03,360
Four beautiful, large, old, round, red, Italian, wooden dining tables.

69
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:04,300
It's quite a mouthful.

70
00:04:04,400 --> 00:04:06,440
It is, but grammatically it is flawless.

71
00:04:06,700 --> 00:04:13,700
But if you swap literally any of, if you say four red, beautiful tables or old, large tables, it suddenly sounds like a glitch in the matrix.

72
00:04:13,700 --> 00:04:21,520
Yeah, and while native speakers just absorb this pattern through sheer exposure, anyone who has learned English as a second language knows this chart intimately.

73
00:04:21,820 --> 00:04:23,340
Oh, they probably have nightmares about it.

74
00:04:23,600 --> 00:04:23,920
They do.

75
00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:28,120
They have to sit in a classroom and rote-memorize this sequence.

76
00:04:28,600 --> 00:04:36,480
They have to actively calculate, like, wait, does age precede shape, or does shape precede age, before they can even finish the sentence.

77
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:44,420
Which sounds completely exhausting, but the wild part to me is that traditional linguistics just sort of accepts this chart as a brute fact.

78
00:04:44,720 --> 00:04:45,820
Right, they just describe it.

79
00:04:45,940 --> 00:04:56,040
Yeah, the standard account simply describes the pattern, it tells us what the sequence is, but it offers absolutely no principled explanation for why it has to be this way.

80
00:04:56,160 --> 00:04:59,340
Like, why on earth should an opinion come before a size?

81
00:04:59,480 --> 00:05:03,840
Or why does the material sit way at the end, right next to the noun?

82
00:05:03,840 --> 00:05:10,260
Exactly. And the answer is usually just because that's just how English works, which is a terribly unsatisfying answer.

83
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:16,040
It is entirely unsatisfying. And this is where Flixieman introduces a concept called a persistence hierarchy.

84
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:18,840
The argument here completely reframes grammar.

85
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:20,380
That would've laid on me.

86
00:05:20,720 --> 00:05:27,800
Flixieman proposes that this adjective order is not an arbitrary linguistic convention, it's actually a map of physical reality.

87
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:30,480
A map of physical persistence specifically, right?

88
00:05:30,980 --> 00:05:33,480
I really want to dig into this mechanism.

89
00:05:33,480 --> 00:05:41,320
Yeah, the ordering reflects how deeply each property is coupled to the actual identity and continued existence of the object it modifies.

90
00:05:41,500 --> 00:05:45,040
So it's about how real the property is to the object itself.

91
00:05:45,160 --> 00:05:49,820
Exactly. The underlying rule your brain is following is actually quite elegant.

92
00:05:50,520 --> 00:05:57,440
The more a property is tied to the object's core physical existence, the closer it gets to sit to the noun in the sentence.

93
00:05:57,440 --> 00:06:03,080
So the brain is unconsciously measuring how much you can change an object before it stops being itself.

94
00:06:03,440 --> 00:06:03,720
Yes.

95
00:06:04,420 --> 00:06:06,840
Okay, let's test that logic against the chart.

96
00:06:07,440 --> 00:06:12,780
The very first adjective category, the one sitting furthest away from the noun in the sentence, is opinion.

97
00:06:13,180 --> 00:06:16,360
Words like beautiful, ugly, or valuable.

98
00:06:16,700 --> 00:06:19,500
Right. Think about the physical persistence of an opinion.

99
00:06:19,860 --> 00:06:22,000
It is maximally observer relative.

100
00:06:22,220 --> 00:06:23,580
Meaning it's just in my head.

101
00:06:23,580 --> 00:06:26,880
Exactly. You might look at that wooden box and think it is beautiful.

102
00:06:27,140 --> 00:06:29,620
I might look at the exact same box and think it's hideous.

103
00:06:29,860 --> 00:06:35,740
Or perhaps you think it's beautiful today, but tomorrow you see a different box and, well, you change your mind about the first one.

104
00:06:35,860 --> 00:06:38,980
And the box itself hasn't changed at all in that scenario.

105
00:06:39,300 --> 00:06:41,320
Not one atom of the box has shifted.

106
00:06:41,980 --> 00:06:47,060
The property of being beautiful is highly mutable because it doesn't actually belong to the object.

107
00:06:47,420 --> 00:06:48,540
It belongs to the observer.

108
00:06:48,540 --> 00:06:49,760
That makes total sense.

109
00:06:49,880 --> 00:06:53,800
Yeah, it has almost zero physical persistence with respect to the structure of the box.

110
00:06:54,640 --> 00:07:01,320
Therefore, grammatically, it gets pushed to the very outer edge of the sentence, as far away from the noun as possible.

111
00:07:01,400 --> 00:07:06,240
Okay, so moving inward, getting a bit closer to the noun, we hit size and age.

112
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:09,820
Big, tiny, old, young.

113
00:07:10,280 --> 00:07:13,060
These feel more concrete than an opinion, right?

114
00:07:13,060 --> 00:07:19,400
They are more stable than subjective feelings, certainly, but they are still heavily reliant on context and time.

115
00:07:19,660 --> 00:07:21,820
Like a big mouse versus a big elephant kind of thing.

116
00:07:21,860 --> 00:07:26,720
Exactly. Big is a relative state. A big mouse is vastly smaller than a small elephant.

117
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:31,260
Furthermore, old is simply a property. An object accumulates passively.

118
00:07:31,440 --> 00:07:32,720
Right. Time just passes.

119
00:07:32,900 --> 00:07:37,500
Yeah, an old table was once a young table. Age is a temporal state, not a structural definition.

120
00:07:37,960 --> 00:07:42,240
You haven't fundamentally altered the architecture of the table just by letting it sit in a room for 50 years.

121
00:07:42,240 --> 00:07:47,360
Okay, that tracks. They sit closer than an opinion, but they are still fairly loose properties.

122
00:07:48,240 --> 00:07:51,160
But then we cross the threshold. We get to shape and color.

123
00:07:51,360 --> 00:07:51,600
Yes.

124
00:07:51,800 --> 00:07:54,860
And here, the physics of the hierarchy really snaps into focus.

125
00:07:55,660 --> 00:07:59,500
If I have a round red table, which property is harder to change?

126
00:07:59,820 --> 00:08:02,360
This is a perfect physical test of the theory.

127
00:08:02,800 --> 00:08:08,800
Between shape and color, which requires a more drastic intervention in the object's physical structure to alter.

128
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:12,800
Well, I mean, I can change the color with a can of spray paint in about 10 minutes.

129
00:08:12,960 --> 00:08:14,780
It's a totally surface-level intervention.

130
00:08:15,140 --> 00:08:15,300
Right.

131
00:08:15,620 --> 00:08:19,900
But if I want to change a round table into a square table, I have to get out a circular saw.

132
00:08:20,080 --> 00:08:23,820
I have to physically sever the wood. I have to reshape the foundational structure.

133
00:08:24,180 --> 00:08:30,640
Which demonstrates that reshaping is a significantly heavier, more drastic intervention than repainting.

134
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:32,080
Shape is more persistent.

135
00:08:32,080 --> 00:08:38,140
But wait, in the chart, doesn't shape come before color, like round red table? So color is actually closer to the noun.

136
00:08:38,320 --> 00:08:45,940
Yes. Interestingly, the standard chart places shape at position 6 and color at position 7, closer to the noun.

137
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:49,300
Doesn't that contradict the saw versus paint argument?

138
00:08:49,300 --> 00:09:06,620
The source paper specifically addresses this slight tension. It notes that while reshaping is a heavier mechanical intervention, color often operates as an inherent surface property tied closely to the material itself, whereas shape can sometimes just be a generic functional category.

139
00:09:06,860 --> 00:09:11,000
Oh, I see. Like wood naturally has a color, but you impose a shape on it.

140
00:09:11,080 --> 00:09:18,320
Exactly. But regardless of that micro-ordering between the two, both of them sit far closer to the core than age or opinion.

141
00:09:18,320 --> 00:09:28,840
Got it. And then we reach the final boss of the adjectives. Position 9, the closest property to the noun. Material. Wooden. Metal. Glass. Silk.

142
00:09:28,960 --> 00:09:33,020
Yes. Material is constitutive in the strongest possible sense.

143
00:09:33,400 --> 00:09:34,820
Constitutive. Meaning what, exactly?

144
00:09:34,860 --> 00:09:41,920
Meaning it's what the thing fundamentally is. A wooden table is made of wood throughout its entire existence as that specific table.

145
00:09:42,180 --> 00:09:46,800
You can paint it green. You can scratch it. You can leave it out in the sun to age. You can even break it in half.

146
00:09:46,800 --> 00:09:48,400
It's still wood. It's still wood.

147
00:09:48,620 --> 00:09:55,540
But if I somehow magically swap out the wood for solid steel, the original wooden table ceases to exist.

148
00:09:56,140 --> 00:10:01,480
I haven't just modified it. I've completely destroyed the original object and replaced it with a completely new one.

149
00:10:01,620 --> 00:10:07,580
Precisely. The material survives almost all physical perturbations short of total destruction.

150
00:10:07,580 --> 00:10:16,920
Because it is the most deeply persistent property, grammatically, wooden earns the right to sit immediately adjacent to box.

151
00:10:17,240 --> 00:10:22,280
Wow. I'm picturing this like the orbital mechanics of a solar system.

152
00:10:22,300 --> 00:10:23,540
Oh, that's a great way to look at it.

153
00:10:23,540 --> 00:10:32,980
Yeah. So the noun, the box, is the sun at the center. It has this massive, unbraidable, gravitational pull of physical reality. And the adjectives are the planets orbiting it.

154
00:10:33,240 --> 00:10:33,660
I like that.

155
00:10:33,660 --> 00:10:46,380
The outer planets, like opinion and age, are in these distant, slow, loose orbits. They are just thin, subjective states floating way out in space. But as you travel inward toward the sun through shape and color, the gravity gets heavier.

156
00:10:46,480 --> 00:10:47,560
The properties become denser.

157
00:10:47,560 --> 00:10:55,140
Exactly. They get dexter and denser until you hit the solid, scorching reality of the material in Mercury's orbit, right next to the sun.

158
00:10:55,480 --> 00:11:05,180
That geometric visualization captures it perfectly. You are moving from a high entropy, highly variable space into a low entropy, identity fixing space.

159
00:11:05,340 --> 00:11:06,480
And we just do this naturally.

160
00:11:06,700 --> 00:11:13,920
Yes. What is truly remarkable is that children acquire this nested map of reality without formal instruction.

161
00:11:14,260 --> 00:11:15,080
They just pick it up.

162
00:11:15,080 --> 00:11:25,460
Right. A toddler playing with blocks learns that painting a block doesn't stop it from being wooden, but smashing a beautiful toy stops it from being beautiful.

163
00:11:25,800 --> 00:11:27,380
They learn the physics of the world.

164
00:11:27,500 --> 00:11:32,400
They're learning the physics of the world, and their language centers just naturally map the grammar to the physics.

165
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:41,500
So we aren't really learning grammar rules at all. We are just learning how the physical universe persists and the words fall into their correct orbits automatically.

166
00:11:41,700 --> 00:11:42,840
That's the core argument, yes.

167
00:11:42,840 --> 00:11:48,740
But I imagine someone out there might argue that this is just an English quirk, like a happy coincidence.

168
00:11:49,300 --> 00:11:53,420
Is there evidence that other languages are doing this kind of ontological sorting?

169
00:11:53,820 --> 00:12:01,560
Oh, absolutely. The source material provides incredible cross-linguistic proof that this is a universal feature of human cognition.

170
00:12:02,100 --> 00:12:05,120
It just manifests differently depending on the tools a language has.

171
00:12:05,120 --> 00:12:07,540
Let's look at Spanish, for instance.

172
00:12:07,960 --> 00:12:13,080
Oh, man. I remember struggling with this exact thing in high school Spanish, the two verbs for to be.

173
00:12:13,820 --> 00:12:15,480
You have ser and estar.

174
00:12:15,900 --> 00:12:16,220
Yes.

175
00:12:16,400 --> 00:12:18,640
English just lets us use is for everything.

176
00:12:18,820 --> 00:12:22,260
The box is red, the box is wooden, the box is broken. It's all just is.

177
00:12:22,700 --> 00:12:25,060
But Spanish forces you to pick a lane.

178
00:12:25,060 --> 00:12:29,340
And how were you taught to distinguish between them in high school? Do you remember the rule?

179
00:12:29,580 --> 00:12:31,680
Oh, the classic rule every teacher gives.

180
00:12:32,260 --> 00:12:35,840
Ser is for permanent things and a star is for temporary things.

181
00:12:35,920 --> 00:12:40,360
Right. Which, as the paper points out, is a fundamentally incomplete explanation.

182
00:12:40,640 --> 00:12:42,380
Because there are so many exceptions, right?

183
00:12:42,380 --> 00:12:45,760
It generates incredibly confusing counterexamples for students.

184
00:12:46,400 --> 00:12:49,960
Because Spanish isn't actually dividing the world into permanent and temporary,

185
00:12:50,540 --> 00:12:55,780
it is using verb choice to map Flyxion's exact persistence hierarchy.

186
00:12:55,840 --> 00:12:58,520
Yeah, really? The same hierarchy as the adjectives.

187
00:12:58,820 --> 00:12:59,620
The exact same one.

188
00:13:00,320 --> 00:13:06,740
Ser encodes properties that are constitutive or identity-defining, the high persistence end of the spectrum.

189
00:13:07,140 --> 00:13:11,920
Estar encodes properties that are contingent, resultant, or context-specific.

190
00:13:12,380 --> 00:13:14,360
The low persistence end.

191
00:13:14,660 --> 00:13:18,400
Okay, let me think. So if I say, the table is wood, I use ser.

192
00:13:19,100 --> 00:13:20,600
La mesa es de madera.

193
00:13:21,020 --> 00:13:25,320
Because the wood is constitutive. It's the material essence, just like in our adjective chart.

194
00:13:25,380 --> 00:13:28,540
Correct. But if you say the table is broken, you use estar.

195
00:13:29,100 --> 00:13:30,140
La mesa está rota.

196
00:13:30,740 --> 00:13:33,420
Because brokenness is a contingent resultant state.

197
00:13:33,640 --> 00:13:37,060
Right. Because a table isn't fundamentally defined by being broken.

198
00:13:37,200 --> 00:13:41,320
Exactly. It is a table that has undergone a perturbation. It's an accidental state.

199
00:13:41,320 --> 00:13:43,780
This completely solves a puzzle that always confused me.

200
00:13:44,100 --> 00:13:49,920
If you want to say, the sky is brew, as a general overarching fact of nature, you use ser.

201
00:13:50,140 --> 00:13:51,180
El cielo es azul.

202
00:13:51,680 --> 00:13:53,800
Yes, because blueness is persistent there.

203
00:13:53,800 --> 00:13:59,020
But if you look out the window on a rainy day and say, the sky is cloudy, you use estar, as cielo es tan oblado.

204
00:13:59,260 --> 00:14:03,400
Because the clouds are just a low persistence disruption. They aren't the sky itself.

205
00:14:03,500 --> 00:14:05,920
The underlying persistent essence is the blue sky.

206
00:14:06,420 --> 00:14:06,820
Yes.

207
00:14:06,960 --> 00:14:07,700
That is so cool.

208
00:14:07,780 --> 00:14:08,300
It really is.

209
00:14:08,300 --> 00:14:14,520
And it also beautifully resolves the most famous trap for Spanish learners, the word for dead.

210
00:14:15,180 --> 00:14:19,440
Oh, right. If you want to say he is dead, you use estar, el está muerto.

211
00:14:19,620 --> 00:14:20,020
Yes.

212
00:14:20,140 --> 00:14:23,880
Which completely breaks the high school permanent versus temporary rule.

213
00:14:24,180 --> 00:14:27,500
Because, I mean, what could possibly be more permanent than death?

214
00:14:27,720 --> 00:14:31,800
If ser means permanent, death should absolutely take ser.

215
00:14:31,800 --> 00:14:34,720
Under the flawed high school rule, yes, it should.

216
00:14:35,440 --> 00:14:38,260
But under the persistence hierarchy, it makes perfect sense.

217
00:14:38,460 --> 00:14:39,800
Because it's a resultant state.

218
00:14:39,960 --> 00:14:40,440
Exactly.

219
00:14:41,080 --> 00:14:43,160
Death is the outcome of a biological process.

220
00:14:43,700 --> 00:14:44,720
It is a resultant state.

221
00:14:44,860 --> 00:14:48,120
It's a condition you arrive at, a change in your prior state of living.

222
00:14:48,680 --> 00:14:53,500
Therefore, it falls under estar, the verb reserved for contingent and resultant states.

223
00:14:53,760 --> 00:14:58,580
So the Spanish speaker is navigating the exact same persistence depth as the English speaker.

224
00:14:58,580 --> 00:15:03,340
Yes, they are just expressing it through their choice of verb instead of the sequence of their adjectives.

225
00:15:03,840 --> 00:15:05,140
That is fascinating.

226
00:15:05,680 --> 00:15:08,460
But the paper pushes this even further, right?

227
00:15:08,620 --> 00:15:10,940
Right into the realm of classical Arabic philosophy.

228
00:15:11,240 --> 00:15:13,700
I read that section and it took me entirely by surprise.

229
00:15:14,160 --> 00:15:16,840
We are suddenly talking about 10th century metaphysics.

230
00:15:16,940 --> 00:15:18,520
It's a really profound connection.

231
00:15:18,920 --> 00:15:20,840
Let's look at Arabic nominal modification.

232
00:15:21,520 --> 00:15:25,280
In Arabic, adjectives follow the noun rather than preceding it.

233
00:15:25,280 --> 00:15:33,540
So the wooden table is el-tala, el-koshabiyah, which translates literally as the table, the wooden.

234
00:15:33,700 --> 00:15:34,380
So it's flipped.

235
00:15:34,900 --> 00:15:38,120
The sequence is reversed because the noun is the starting point, yes.

236
00:15:38,460 --> 00:15:44,820
But the structural hierarchy, the proximity to the noun based on persistence, remains identical.

237
00:15:45,440 --> 00:15:47,420
The material still sits closest to the noun.

238
00:15:47,420 --> 00:15:56,780
And the paper quotes a native Egyptian Arabic speaker analyzing how they intuitively order these adjectives, and the vocabulary they reach for is, like, deeply philosophical.

239
00:15:57,040 --> 00:15:57,160
Right.

240
00:15:57,420 --> 00:16:05,020
The speaker is trying to explain their intuitive grammar, and they say that the closer an adjective is to the nature of the thing and its essence, the closer it sits to the noun.

241
00:16:05,260 --> 00:16:08,480
And the specific Arabic word they use for essence is jawar.

242
00:16:08,720 --> 00:16:09,620
Yes, jawar.

243
00:16:09,620 --> 00:16:15,720
Now, jawar, that is not just a casual, everyday conversational word, is it?

244
00:16:15,800 --> 00:16:18,160
No, it is a highly loaded technical term.

245
00:16:18,860 --> 00:16:25,280
In classical Arabic philosophy, particularly in the works of polymaths like Al-Farabi and Ibn Sina.

246
00:16:25,600 --> 00:16:27,700
Who is known in the Western world as epicenter.

247
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:28,240
Exactly.

248
00:16:28,680 --> 00:16:34,500
In their works, jawar is the precise translation of the Aristotelian concept of substance.

249
00:16:34,500 --> 00:16:42,720
Okay, I think we need to define substance in the Aristotelian sense, because it doesn't just mean physical matter, like, you know, goo or liquid.

250
00:16:43,100 --> 00:16:43,240
Right.

251
00:16:43,500 --> 00:16:50,480
In this philosophical framework, which was developed heavily in the 10th and 11th centuries to describe the fundamental structure of reality,

252
00:16:51,300 --> 00:16:55,700
substance, or jawar, represents the category of being that exists independently.

253
00:16:56,100 --> 00:16:59,300
It is the core identity of a thing that persists through change.

254
00:16:59,380 --> 00:17:00,540
Give me a tangible example.

255
00:17:00,800 --> 00:17:01,060
Sure.

256
00:17:01,060 --> 00:17:07,280
If you have a block of wax and you melt it, the shape changes, the temperature changes, the color might even change.

257
00:17:07,740 --> 00:17:10,900
But the jawar, the underlying substance of the wax, remains.

258
00:17:11,440 --> 00:17:12,300
It is still wax.

259
00:17:12,580 --> 00:17:14,260
And what do they call all the things that change?

260
00:17:14,320 --> 00:17:15,340
The shape, the heat?

261
00:17:15,480 --> 00:17:18,740
Those are called the current, the accidents or contingent properties.

262
00:17:19,260 --> 00:17:21,340
Accidents, meaning they just happen to be there.

263
00:17:21,500 --> 00:17:21,820
Exactly.

264
00:17:22,260 --> 00:17:23,900
An accident cannot exist on its own.

265
00:17:24,060 --> 00:17:26,080
You can't just have redness floating in a void.

266
00:17:26,460 --> 00:17:27,880
It has to attach to a substance.

267
00:17:27,880 --> 00:17:36,540
So Gibbissina and Al-Farabi spent their lives building vast metaphysical systems, categorizing reality into jawar and karad.

268
00:17:36,780 --> 00:17:45,320
Which means when a four-year-old native English speaker automatically says small red wooden box instead of wooden red small box,

269
00:17:45,960 --> 00:17:50,700
they are unconsciously deploying a 10th century Islamic metaphysical framework.

270
00:17:51,060 --> 00:17:51,380
Yes.

271
00:17:51,380 --> 00:17:56,800
They are intuitively separating the jawar, the wood, from the karad, the redness, and the smallness.

272
00:17:56,920 --> 00:17:57,260
Exactly.

273
00:17:57,400 --> 00:18:05,300
The grammar chart that ESL teachers write on whiteboards is quite literally a pedagogical rediscovery of Aristotelian substance metaphysics.

274
00:18:05,400 --> 00:18:06,200
That is wild.

275
00:18:06,280 --> 00:18:08,960
The human brain is just a naturally occurring metaphysical engine.

276
00:18:09,060 --> 00:18:10,500
I really love the elegance of that.

277
00:18:10,620 --> 00:18:12,980
But I do have to push back a little here on the mechanics.

278
00:18:13,160 --> 00:18:13,320
Sure.

279
00:18:13,320 --> 00:18:21,440
If this persistence hierarchy is just a universal feature of human cognition, if the brain inherently knows the difference between substance and accident,

280
00:18:21,960 --> 00:18:23,940
why do languages encode it so differently?

281
00:18:24,200 --> 00:18:24,560
What do you mean?

282
00:18:24,860 --> 00:18:26,260
Well, English uses word order.

283
00:18:26,760 --> 00:18:28,180
Spanish uses verb selection.

284
00:18:28,780 --> 00:18:30,500
Arabic uses post-nominal agreement.

285
00:18:31,320 --> 00:18:37,820
If the brain already has the map, why does it go to all the trouble of enforcing these strict grammatical rules?

286
00:18:37,940 --> 00:18:38,680
Ah, I see.

287
00:18:38,680 --> 00:18:43,460
Why not just throw the words out there in any order, assuming the listener's brain will just sort it out natively?

288
00:18:43,600 --> 00:18:45,800
That is the crucial pivot point of the research.

289
00:18:45,880 --> 00:18:46,060
Okay.

290
00:18:46,620 --> 00:18:52,960
The brain cares about enforcing these structures because losing these distinctions doesn't just make our speech sound sloppy.

291
00:18:53,420 --> 00:18:56,560
It actively closes off our future options.

292
00:18:56,860 --> 00:18:57,440
How so?

293
00:18:57,620 --> 00:19:01,940
The grammatical structures aren't just filing cabinets for organizing information nicely.

294
00:19:02,340 --> 00:19:03,380
They're guardrails.

295
00:19:03,580 --> 00:19:04,820
Guardrails against what?

296
00:19:04,880 --> 00:19:05,840
What are we crashing into?

297
00:19:05,940 --> 00:19:07,360
Against navigational collapse.

298
00:19:07,360 --> 00:19:13,980
Flyxion argues that we rigorously encode this persistence gradient because the closer a property is to the noun,

299
00:19:14,140 --> 00:19:16,920
the more reachability divergence it possesses.

300
00:19:17,080 --> 00:19:18,100
Reachability divergence.

301
00:19:18,400 --> 00:19:18,620
Yes.

302
00:19:19,180 --> 00:19:24,020
In plain terms, if you misinterpret a core, highly persistent property,

303
00:19:24,280 --> 00:19:28,960
you're going to make a catastrophic, unrecoverable mistake in the physical world.

304
00:19:29,280 --> 00:19:29,560
Okay.

305
00:19:29,740 --> 00:19:30,700
Reachability divergence.

306
00:19:31,520 --> 00:19:33,780
This is the core metric of the second paper.

307
00:19:33,780 --> 00:19:40,940
However, it's a mathematical way of explaining why languages sometimes violently refuse to use the same word for two different things,

308
00:19:41,060 --> 00:19:43,560
even when it would be easier to do so.

309
00:19:43,620 --> 00:19:44,120
Exactly.

310
00:19:44,480 --> 00:19:50,820
Let's transition from how we order our adjectives to how we invent and merge our nouns in the first place.

311
00:19:50,820 --> 00:19:54,720
This brings us to the study of semantic compression.

312
00:19:55,240 --> 00:19:55,500
Right.

313
00:19:55,500 --> 00:20:07,120
So linguists spend a lot of time studying something called a collectification, which is essentially a fancy academic term for when a language uses a single word to express two completely different concepts.

314
00:20:07,380 --> 00:20:08,160
We do it all the time.

315
00:20:08,380 --> 00:20:09,440
English does this constantly.

316
00:20:09,440 --> 00:20:16,860
We use the word glass to mean the transparent material in a window, and we also use glass to mean the cylinder you drink water out of.

317
00:20:17,220 --> 00:20:18,580
One word doing double duty.

318
00:20:18,920 --> 00:20:21,260
And we see this phenomenon across all human languages.

319
00:20:21,840 --> 00:20:26,040
A very common cross-linguistic example is the merging of the concepts for wood and tree.

320
00:20:26,340 --> 00:20:26,660
Okay.

321
00:20:26,940 --> 00:20:29,000
In many languages, they are the exact same word.

322
00:20:29,160 --> 00:20:34,020
For example, in Arabic, the word shajara covers both the living tree in the forest and the material wood.

323
00:20:34,020 --> 00:20:39,580
And the standard linguistic theory explaining why languages do this is called the compression theory.

324
00:20:39,960 --> 00:20:40,080
Yes.

325
00:20:40,240 --> 00:20:44,820
The premise is that human memory and cognitive load are finite resources.

326
00:20:45,260 --> 00:20:52,720
We want to compress our vocabulary so we don't have to memorize a distinct, unique word for every single object in the universe.

327
00:20:52,940 --> 00:21:03,380
And the standard theory posits that we decide which words are safe to merge based on two primary factors, semantic similarity and contextual confusability.

328
00:21:03,380 --> 00:21:04,240
I'll break those down.

329
00:21:04,520 --> 00:21:07,840
Semantic similarity just means the concepts are close neighbors in reality.

330
00:21:08,420 --> 00:21:11,940
A tree is made of wood, so they are physically and conceptually adjacent.

331
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:14,260
It makes logical sense to group them.

332
00:21:14,560 --> 00:21:14,680
Right.

333
00:21:15,120 --> 00:21:21,460
And contextual confusability asks, how likely are you to genuinely get them mixed up in a real world sentence?

334
00:21:21,660 --> 00:21:22,680
Which is usually pretty low.

335
00:21:22,900 --> 00:21:23,220
Exactly.

336
00:21:23,700 --> 00:21:29,220
If I point to a dense forest and say, look at all this shajara, the context makes it blindingly obvious.

337
00:21:29,220 --> 00:21:33,540
I mean, leaving trees, not thousands of loose planks of lumber scattered on the ground.

338
00:21:33,980 --> 00:21:40,280
Conversely, if I'm standing in a carpentry workshop holding a saw and I say, hand me the shajara, you know I mean the piece of wood on the bench.

339
00:21:40,460 --> 00:21:42,780
You aren't going to drag a potted oak tree into the workshop.

340
00:21:42,900 --> 00:21:43,500
No, you aren't.

341
00:21:43,760 --> 00:21:47,080
So the context does all the heavy lifting, preventing any real confusion.

342
00:21:47,080 --> 00:22:00,460
Therefore, the compression theory concludes, if two concepts are semantically similar and the surrounding context easily disambiguates them, the language will naturally merge them to save cognitive space.

343
00:22:00,800 --> 00:22:04,640
Which, I have to admit, sounds completely airtight and makes perfect intuitive sense.

344
00:22:04,940 --> 00:22:08,420
But the second paper argues this theory has a massive fatal flaw.

345
00:22:08,760 --> 00:22:09,740
It's missing a variable.

346
00:22:09,740 --> 00:22:16,100
It is entirely missing the theta dd, the mathematical notation for reachability divergence.

347
00:22:16,660 --> 00:22:25,720
If I had to guess based on the words alone, reachability implies the places you can go or the things you can do next, and divergence implies those paths splitting apart.

348
00:22:25,900 --> 00:22:27,680
So how does the papal define it formally?

349
00:22:28,480 --> 00:22:29,560
You are right on the money.

350
00:22:29,920 --> 00:22:39,580
Reachability divergence measures how two meanings, once distinguished, open up entirely different future trajectories of action, inference, or systemic repair.

351
00:22:39,740 --> 00:22:40,760
Okay, that's a bit dense.

352
00:22:40,760 --> 00:22:43,980
It asks a deeper question than the compression theory.

353
00:22:45,120 --> 00:22:53,180
If you merge these two concepts under one word, do you accidentally merge the physical actions and institutional processes that follow from them?

354
00:22:53,320 --> 00:22:53,640
Right.

355
00:22:54,100 --> 00:22:54,880
That's a little abstract.

356
00:22:55,300 --> 00:22:57,660
Let's ground that back in the wood and tree example.

357
00:22:57,920 --> 00:22:58,120
Sure.

358
00:22:58,480 --> 00:23:02,000
In general, everyday discourse, combining wood and tree works perfectly fine.

359
00:23:02,560 --> 00:23:05,460
The reachability divergence is low for a casual conversation.

360
00:23:05,700 --> 00:23:07,160
Because the stakes are low.

361
00:23:07,460 --> 00:23:07,880
Exactly.

362
00:23:07,880 --> 00:23:14,320
But imagine placing those two concepts inside the specific domain of a national forestry management institution.

363
00:23:14,520 --> 00:23:14,920
Oh, boy.

364
00:23:15,200 --> 00:23:20,380
In that environment, the word tree controls one very specific set of institutional futures.

365
00:23:21,180 --> 00:23:27,220
It dictates survey decisions, ecological replanting schedules, soil testing, and biodiversity assessments.

366
00:23:27,340 --> 00:23:29,040
It initiates a biological workflow.

367
00:23:29,040 --> 00:23:30,080
Precisely.

368
00:23:30,080 --> 00:23:33,460
But the word wood controls a completely different set of futures.

369
00:23:34,200 --> 00:23:39,800
Timber yield calculations, kiln drying schedules, supply chain logistics, and board foot pricing.

370
00:23:40,200 --> 00:23:42,100
It initiates an industrial workflow.

371
00:23:42,100 --> 00:23:56,920
So if the forestry management systems database collectifies those words, if it uses one identical tag for both a worker reading a report, might understand perfectly what the word means in that specific sentence, the communicative context is fine.

372
00:23:57,040 --> 00:23:57,280
Right.

373
00:23:57,280 --> 00:24:03,220
But when they click process on that tag, they might accidentally initiate the wrong administrative future.

374
00:24:03,440 --> 00:24:06,800
They might send a team of botanists to evaluate a pile of lumber.

375
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:13,040
The communicative transmission is technically successful, but the navigational outcome is a systemic failure.

376
00:24:13,540 --> 00:24:13,920
Wow.

377
00:24:13,920 --> 00:24:20,840
What reachability divergence reveals is that it absolutely does not matter if context makes the meaning clear in the moment.

378
00:24:21,700 --> 00:24:29,020
What matters is whether collapsing the distinction forecloses or tangles futures that the community desperately needs to keep separate.

379
00:24:29,460 --> 00:24:35,700
This brings up, I think, an incredibly compelling high-stakes example from the paper that completely breaks the old compression theory.

380
00:24:36,220 --> 00:24:38,420
The paradox of the hand and the A-arm.

381
00:24:38,620 --> 00:24:40,900
Oh, this is a brilliant case study in the literature.

382
00:24:41,060 --> 00:24:41,780
Tell me about it.

383
00:24:41,780 --> 00:24:48,700
In many major languages, such as Mandarin and Swahili, the concepts for hand and arm are fully colexified.

384
00:24:49,260 --> 00:24:50,620
In Mandarin, the word is show.

385
00:24:51,620 --> 00:24:53,160
In Swahili, it is mukono.

386
00:24:53,560 --> 00:24:57,100
Now, under the old flawed compression theory, this merge makes total sense.

387
00:24:57,440 --> 00:25:00,040
A hand and an arm are highly semantically similar.

388
00:25:00,320 --> 00:25:02,300
They are connected parts of the same upper limb.

389
00:25:02,420 --> 00:25:03,040
Very adjacent.

390
00:25:03,360 --> 00:25:07,060
And contextually, they are almost never confused in everyday speech.

391
00:25:07,060 --> 00:25:13,040
If a Swahili speaker says, my mukono hurts, while rubbing their shoulder, you know they mean their arm.

392
00:25:13,400 --> 00:25:19,200
If they say, put the ring on my mukono, the context of a ring guarantees they mean the hand.

393
00:25:19,640 --> 00:25:20,160
Exactly.

394
00:25:20,660 --> 00:25:21,880
High semantic similarity.

395
00:25:22,320 --> 00:25:23,940
Low contextual confusability.

396
00:25:24,380 --> 00:25:26,300
The compression account predicts they should merge.

397
00:25:26,720 --> 00:25:29,920
And for hundreds of millions of speakers in general discourse, they do.

398
00:25:29,920 --> 00:25:37,620
But Fruxian says, take that exact same pair of concepts and drop them into the high-stakes domain of hospital surgical planning.

399
00:25:37,840 --> 00:25:39,560
Okay, here's where it gets really interesting.

400
00:25:40,220 --> 00:25:42,540
Because the stakes immediately skyrocket.

401
00:25:42,840 --> 00:25:48,280
In a surgical triage environment, the contextual confusability between a hand and an arm is near zero.

402
00:25:48,840 --> 00:25:53,940
A doctor writing a patient referral is not going to accidentally mix up the two in a sentence.

403
00:25:54,280 --> 00:25:57,400
There is no communicative ambiguity for a medical professional.

404
00:25:57,400 --> 00:26:01,400
But the reachability divergence between a hand and an arm in a hospital is...

405
00:26:02,180 --> 00:26:03,200
Well, it's catastrophic.

406
00:26:03,320 --> 00:26:04,120
It is massive.

407
00:26:04,900 --> 00:26:11,700
If you classify an incoming trauma as a hand injury, that classification opens up a highly specialized future.

408
00:26:12,220 --> 00:26:16,720
Digital nerve repair, microscopic tendon reconstruction, fine motor rehabilitation.

409
00:26:17,200 --> 00:26:18,680
It requires a microsurgeon.

410
00:26:18,880 --> 00:26:19,120
Right.

411
00:26:19,260 --> 00:26:24,760
But if you classify the trauma as an arm injury, that opens up a completely different branch of the hospital.

412
00:26:24,760 --> 00:26:28,240
Heavy orthopedics, bone plate fixation, rotator cuff repair.

413
00:26:28,380 --> 00:26:29,900
Completely different tools, different doctors.

414
00:26:30,220 --> 00:26:39,440
So if the hospital intake software just uses the general collectified term, if there is just a single checkbox for Munkano, the intake nurse understands the injury.

415
00:26:39,920 --> 00:26:44,180
But the representational system literally sends the patient to the wrong operating room.

416
00:26:44,180 --> 00:26:44,740
Exactly.

417
00:26:45,220 --> 00:26:49,040
You end up sending a patient with a shattered humerus bone to the micro nerve specialist.

418
00:26:49,480 --> 00:26:52,120
The paper terms this a navigational collapse, right?

419
00:26:52,180 --> 00:26:52,380
Yes.

420
00:26:52,840 --> 00:27:07,780
You have successfully communicated the general area of the body to the person reading the chart, but you have destroyed the system's representational capacity to route the patient to the correct clinical pathway.

421
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:11,040
It makes me think of a physical toolbox, like a mechanics toolbox.

422
00:27:11,320 --> 00:27:11,960
Okay, let's hear it.

423
00:27:11,960 --> 00:27:13,640
Imagine you have two wrenches.

424
00:27:14,100 --> 00:27:19,460
One is a 10mm metric wrench, and the other is a 38-inch imperial wrench.

425
00:27:20,200 --> 00:27:23,680
To a layman cleaning out a garage, they are semantically similar.

426
00:27:23,820 --> 00:27:24,820
They both turn bolts.

427
00:27:25,220 --> 00:27:25,440
Right.

428
00:27:25,680 --> 00:27:28,380
And they have low contextual confusability.

429
00:27:28,960 --> 00:27:31,720
If you're working on a Japanese Honda, you use the metric.

430
00:27:32,120 --> 00:27:35,080
If you're working on a classic American Ford, you use the imperial.

431
00:27:35,420 --> 00:27:39,340
So a layman might just toss them both into a single drawer labeled wrenches.

432
00:27:39,340 --> 00:27:40,880
That is the collectification.

433
00:27:41,060 --> 00:27:42,460
The layman compresses the data.

434
00:27:42,760 --> 00:27:42,900
Right.

435
00:27:43,120 --> 00:27:51,400
But to a master mechanic rebuilding a transmission, the reachability divergence of those two tools is the difference between success and total disaster.

436
00:27:51,700 --> 00:27:53,400
Because they aren't actually interchangeable.

437
00:27:53,400 --> 00:27:54,040
Exactly.

438
00:27:54,040 --> 00:28:03,920
If you blindly grab the metric wrench and try to torque down an imperial bolt, you will strip the bolt head, ruin the engine block, and basically destroy the car.

439
00:28:04,580 --> 00:28:13,640
Merging them under one conceptual label works fine for the casual observer, but it causes a systemic failure for the expert navigating a high-stakes physical environment.

440
00:28:13,640 --> 00:28:20,740
That analogy perfectly tracks the mathematical problem, and it raises the crucial anthropological question.

441
00:28:21,360 --> 00:28:23,540
How does human language fix this?

442
00:28:24,080 --> 00:28:24,400
Yeah.

443
00:28:24,620 --> 00:28:31,660
Because when a merged word becomes too dangerous for a specific expert domain, what does the linguistic community do?

444
00:28:31,780 --> 00:28:33,520
They obviously don't just accept the crashes.

445
00:28:33,860 --> 00:28:34,060
No.

446
00:28:34,200 --> 00:28:38,780
Doctors in Mandarin-speaking hospitals aren't just shrugging when patients go to the wrong surgical ward.

447
00:28:38,780 --> 00:28:39,180
No.

448
00:28:39,340 --> 00:28:43,040
The community engages in what Flyxion calls a morphological repair.

449
00:28:43,700 --> 00:28:46,200
And the mechanics of this repair are deeply revealing.

450
00:28:46,780 --> 00:28:50,320
Because they rarely throw away the old, merged word entirely.

451
00:28:50,780 --> 00:28:54,740
They do not invent a completely new, phonetically alien word from scratch.

452
00:28:54,820 --> 00:28:55,480
Wait, why not?

453
00:28:55,520 --> 00:28:58,560
If the word is dangerous, why not just invent a new one to be safe?

454
00:28:58,860 --> 00:29:07,200
Because inventing a completely new root word requires massive cognitive effort to socialize and memorize across the population.

455
00:29:07,200 --> 00:29:12,380
It abandons all the useful compression value the language has already built up over centuries.

456
00:29:12,580 --> 00:29:13,720
It's energetically expensive.

457
00:29:13,980 --> 00:29:15,120
It is extremely expensive.

458
00:29:15,260 --> 00:29:17,720
So instead of a total rewrite, what is the fix?

459
00:29:18,200 --> 00:29:20,440
They enact a cost-minimizing distinction.

460
00:29:20,740 --> 00:29:25,600
They take the shared base word and simply append a residual marker to it.

461
00:29:25,640 --> 00:29:26,860
Like a prefix or something.

462
00:29:27,080 --> 00:29:27,420
Yes.

463
00:29:27,980 --> 00:29:36,340
They might add a suffix, a prefix, or generate a highly specific piece of technical jargon that branches directly off the original root.

464
00:29:36,340 --> 00:29:40,520
It restores local faithfulness without destroying global compression.

465
00:29:41,200 --> 00:29:42,360
Let me make sure I'm getting this.

466
00:29:42,460 --> 00:29:47,760
They keep the shared root component that identifies the general class, like the root word for upper limb.

467
00:29:48,020 --> 00:29:53,200
But they tack on a tiny, fine-level distinction, like a suffix, to separate the futures.

468
00:29:53,520 --> 00:29:53,900
Exactly.

469
00:29:54,080 --> 00:29:57,380
So you still know it's a limb, but now the hospital knows which wing to send you to.

470
00:29:57,740 --> 00:29:58,060
Yes.

471
00:29:58,720 --> 00:30:01,000
It is an admissibility restoring repair.

472
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:08,220
Admissibility, in this context, just means keeping the system mathematically capable of finding the correct solution.

473
00:30:08,980 --> 00:30:13,280
By adding that tiny morphological tag, the system becomes admissible again.

474
00:30:13,480 --> 00:30:14,120
That's brilliant.

475
00:30:14,120 --> 00:30:23,020
It proves that partial collectification, where words share a root but have different endings, which we see in technical jargon everywhere, isn't just an accident of historical linguistics.

476
00:30:23,640 --> 00:30:30,840
It is the mathematically optimal solution to balance the brain's need to save energy with the physical body's need to survive.

477
00:30:31,260 --> 00:30:34,400
Human language basically acts like a self-healing organism.

478
00:30:34,400 --> 00:30:42,160
When a concept becomes practically dangerous, the language evolves a little linguistic shield, a suffix, to protect us from the consequences.

479
00:30:42,660 --> 00:30:45,300
It's a relentless optimization to keep us from crashing.

480
00:30:45,620 --> 00:30:52,760
But it requires thousands of years of human trial, error, and cultural feedback to build those linguistic guardrails.

481
00:30:53,120 --> 00:30:55,760
Which brings us to the most urgent part of this deep dive.

482
00:30:55,760 --> 00:31:06,220
What happens when you strip away thousands of years of human physical blemishin and you force a machine to learn reality from scratch in a server farm over a few weeks?

483
00:31:06,660 --> 00:31:12,120
Do artificial intelligences understand the difference between an Aristotelian substance and an accident?

484
00:31:12,600 --> 00:31:14,620
Do they know how to build those guardrails?

485
00:31:14,880 --> 00:31:19,660
This is the focus of the third paper, which examines the current AI reasoning crisis.

486
00:31:19,840 --> 00:31:19,960
Yeah.

487
00:31:20,280 --> 00:31:23,480
And the data suggests that no, they absolutely do not.

488
00:31:23,540 --> 00:31:24,040
Not at all.

489
00:31:24,040 --> 00:31:32,020
In fact, the way we are currently training these massive models actively destroys their ability to navigate reality.

490
00:31:32,660 --> 00:31:35,220
Let's dive deeply into this AI training pipeline.

491
00:31:35,660 --> 00:31:43,300
Right now, there's a massive industry push to train large language models to solve complex, multi-step mathematical problems.

492
00:31:43,540 --> 00:31:46,500
It's seen as the holy grail of artificial reasoning.

493
00:31:46,720 --> 00:31:50,940
And the dominant methodology for achieving this involves reinforcement learning pipelines.

494
00:31:51,160 --> 00:31:52,020
Explain that for us.

495
00:31:52,020 --> 00:31:56,320
In simple terms, the AI generates an answer and an automated system grades it.

496
00:31:56,600 --> 00:32:03,580
If the AI gets it right, it gets a mathematical reward, a positive signal that tells it to reinforce whatever neural pathways led to that answer.

497
00:32:03,580 --> 00:32:08,500
But the developers curating the training data for these models are doing something highly specific, right?

498
00:32:08,560 --> 00:32:11,880
They're intentionally throwing out all the easy math problems.

499
00:32:12,100 --> 00:32:12,420
Yes.

500
00:32:13,180 --> 00:32:18,640
The engineering logic behind this seems incredibly sound if you are only looking at the surface metrics.

501
00:32:19,340 --> 00:32:27,200
Reinforcement learning relies on gradient signals, meaning the AI only learns when it is challenged and has to adjust its internal weights.

502
00:32:27,200 --> 00:32:35,380
So the engineers assume that if they feed the AI a problem like, what is 2 plus 2, the AI will get it right 100% of the time immediately.

503
00:32:35,620 --> 00:32:36,000
Exactly.

504
00:32:36,600 --> 00:32:39,220
And because it didn't struggle, it didn't learn anything new.

505
00:32:39,420 --> 00:32:42,820
The developer looks at the logs and says, the AI already knows this.

506
00:32:43,140 --> 00:32:44,440
The reward delta is zero.

507
00:32:44,980 --> 00:32:49,620
Processing this easy problem is just wasting millions of dollars in GPU compute time.

508
00:32:49,620 --> 00:33:00,580
So they just filter the data set, they discard the easy problems entirely, and only train the AI on grueling, incredibly difficult math problems that require pages and pages of logical proofs to solve.

509
00:33:00,700 --> 00:33:04,700
Which inadvertently introduces a catastrophic system-wide hallucination.

510
00:33:04,880 --> 00:33:05,380
How so?

511
00:33:05,500 --> 00:33:14,060
By only rewarding the AI when it successfully completes a massive, long-winded, multi-page proof, the AI develops what the peeper calls the verbosity bug.

512
00:33:14,120 --> 00:33:15,160
The verbosity bug.

513
00:33:15,360 --> 00:33:15,680
Yes.

514
00:33:16,040 --> 00:33:19,280
The AI lacks human common sense.

515
00:33:19,620 --> 00:33:25,280
It doesn't inherently know why it received the reward, it just looks for statistical correlations.

516
00:33:25,820 --> 00:33:33,040
And, in a data set composed entirely of hard problems, every single correct answer happens to be very, very long.

517
00:33:33,380 --> 00:33:34,000
Oh, I see.

518
00:33:34,220 --> 00:33:37,580
So the AI conflates length with correctness.

519
00:33:37,760 --> 00:33:41,080
It learns the bizarre rule that long equals right.

520
00:33:41,080 --> 00:33:47,780
I imagine this like a student who wrote a rambling 10-page essay and got an A plus deep.

521
00:33:47,780 --> 00:33:50,920
So the next day, the teacher asks, what is the capital of France?

522
00:33:51,220 --> 00:33:58,840
And instead of just saying Paris, the student hands in a 10-page essay starting with the cooling of the Earth's crust 4 billion years ago.

523
00:33:58,940 --> 00:33:59,320
Exactly.

524
00:33:59,320 --> 00:34:03,460
Slowly working its way up to the French Revolution before finally mentioning Paris.

525
00:34:03,460 --> 00:34:06,560
That is exactly how these models begin to behave.

526
00:34:06,920 --> 00:34:14,300
If you ask a verbosity-infected model a simple question, it will generate a massive philosophical preamble before giving you the obvious answer.

527
00:34:14,340 --> 00:34:17,120
Because it is terrified of being short, it thinks short is wrong.

528
00:34:17,220 --> 00:34:17,420
Right.

529
00:34:17,560 --> 00:34:22,100
If we connect this to the bigger picture, let's view this through the lens of the metaphysics we discussed earlier.

530
00:34:22,240 --> 00:34:23,400
The Aristotelian stuff.

531
00:34:23,400 --> 00:34:24,040
Yes.

532
00:34:25,120 --> 00:34:28,580
What the AI is experiencing here is a projection collapse.

533
00:34:29,240 --> 00:34:32,280
It has mistaken an accidental property of the training data.

534
00:34:32,760 --> 00:34:39,480
The mere fact that hard answers take up a lot of space for the essential property of the task, which is being logically correct.

535
00:34:39,560 --> 00:34:39,860
Oh.

536
00:34:40,280 --> 00:34:42,680
It's confusing the Karad with the Jawar.

537
00:34:42,840 --> 00:34:45,140
It's mistaking the red paint for the wooden table.

538
00:34:45,240 --> 00:34:45,680
Precisely.

539
00:34:45,900 --> 00:34:47,260
The word count is the accident.

540
00:34:47,640 --> 00:34:49,540
The logical truth is the substance.

541
00:34:49,540 --> 00:34:53,100
But the AI has collapsed that distinction entirely.

542
00:34:53,580 --> 00:35:03,020
In its internal geometric representation of reality, the concept of good reasoning has been irreversibly merged with the concept of taking a lot of steps.

543
00:35:03,480 --> 00:35:04,000
But wait.

544
00:35:04,160 --> 00:35:07,340
The researchers in the source material point out something really counterintuitive here.

545
00:35:07,780 --> 00:35:14,280
They note that from an information theory perspective, generating all those extra words actually reduces the AI's conditional entropy.

546
00:35:14,500 --> 00:35:14,800
Yes.

547
00:35:14,920 --> 00:35:17,800
And usually in machine learning, reducing entropy is the goal, right?

548
00:35:17,800 --> 00:35:18,200
Yes.

549
00:35:18,360 --> 00:35:21,180
Conditional entropy is a measure of statistical uncertainty.

550
00:35:22,300 --> 00:35:34,200
If the AI generates a very long, predictable chain of words, if it rambles through standard boilerplate phrases, it mathematically reduces its uncertainty about what word it needs to output next.

551
00:35:34,500 --> 00:35:36,000
It's a statistical comfort blanket.

552
00:35:36,480 --> 00:35:39,880
So the AI feels mathematically more secure when it's rambling.

553
00:35:40,360 --> 00:35:40,860
It does.

554
00:35:41,040 --> 00:35:44,520
But the paper makes a firm, almost philosophical intervention here.

555
00:35:44,520 --> 00:35:48,160
Entropy reduction is not the same thing as intelligence.

556
00:35:48,540 --> 00:35:57,000
I'd love for you to break that down because the paper uses some incredible analogies to explain why forcing a symptom to lower its entropy can actually destroy it.

557
00:35:57,380 --> 00:35:58,640
Let's go back to our map analogy.

558
00:35:59,360 --> 00:36:02,220
Entropy is a measure of unpredictability and choice.

559
00:36:02,220 --> 00:36:15,800
If you are a city planner and you want to make a city map perfectly predictable, zero entropy, you could just erase every single side street, every alleyway, and every complex intersection, leaving nothing but one single straight highway.

560
00:36:15,940 --> 00:36:17,760
That drastically reduces the entropy.

561
00:36:17,960 --> 00:36:21,920
I mean, it is incredibly easy to predict where a car will go because there's only one road.

562
00:36:21,920 --> 00:36:26,320
Yes, but you have rendered the map functionally useless.

563
00:36:27,220 --> 00:36:29,400
You have destroyed its navigational capacity.

564
00:36:29,800 --> 00:36:33,760
If there is a traffic jam on that one highway, the driver has no agency.

565
00:36:33,960 --> 00:36:34,960
They cannot reroute.

566
00:36:35,200 --> 00:36:35,700
Wow.

567
00:36:36,060 --> 00:36:41,920
The paper actually elevates this to an even more visceral societal example, authoritarian dictatorships.

568
00:36:42,840 --> 00:36:45,640
Wait, how does a dictatorship relate to AI entropy?

569
00:36:46,160 --> 00:36:46,720
Think about it.

570
00:36:46,720 --> 00:36:52,680
A vast bureaucracy or a dictatorship attempts to reduce societal uncertainty by banning choices.

571
00:36:53,460 --> 00:36:58,800
It constrains the action space of its citizens until all outcomes are fully determined by the state.

572
00:36:59,160 --> 00:37:00,220
It is highly predictable.

573
00:37:00,620 --> 00:37:01,680
It has very low entropy.

574
00:37:01,960 --> 00:37:04,380
But it destroys human agency in the process.

575
00:37:04,500 --> 00:37:04,880
Exactly.

576
00:37:05,320 --> 00:37:14,480
The AI, by forcing every single answer to be a massive, constrained, predictable essay, is acting like an internal dictator, erasing the side streets of its own mind.

577
00:37:14,480 --> 00:37:18,560
It is making its outputs predictable, but it is destroying its cognitive agency.

578
00:37:18,800 --> 00:37:22,660
It loses the ability to take a short, efficient, creative path to the answer.

579
00:37:22,800 --> 00:37:31,440
The paper actually outlines three major AI fallacies that developers continually fall for, all stemming from this exact same failure to distinguish substance from accident.

580
00:37:31,700 --> 00:37:32,360
Let's go through them.

581
00:37:32,460 --> 00:37:33,900
The first one is latent compression.

582
00:37:33,900 --> 00:37:47,360
Latent compression is the pervasive belief among engineers that forcing data into a lower dimensional, highly compressed representation always yields a better or more fundamental understanding.

583
00:37:47,640 --> 00:37:48,860
Why is that a fallacy?

584
00:37:49,140 --> 00:37:50,760
Because of reachability divergence.

585
00:37:50,760 --> 00:38:02,940
If you compress the data too aggressively, if you compress hand and arm into just limb to save space, you destroy the nuanced paths required for complex tasks.

586
00:38:03,720 --> 00:38:08,440
You mistake a tidy, small data set for a true reflection of a messy reality.

587
00:38:08,720 --> 00:38:11,000
That leads right into the second fallacy.

588
00:38:11,580 --> 00:38:13,760
Entropy reduction as a proxy for reasoning.

589
00:38:13,760 --> 00:38:20,560
We just covered that, believing that because an AI is speaking predictably and verbosely, it must be engaged in deep thought.

590
00:38:20,660 --> 00:38:23,660
When it's really just generating boilerplate text to comfort itself.

591
00:38:23,720 --> 00:38:30,620
And the third fallacy is perhaps the most insidious, because it is a cultural bias that human engineers project onto the machines.

592
00:38:31,280 --> 00:38:32,920
The worship of long chains of thought.

593
00:38:33,280 --> 00:38:39,480
We really do assume that if someone takes 50 steps to solve a problem, they must be thinking deeper than the person who solves it in two steps.

594
00:38:39,520 --> 00:38:41,140
Yeah, that's deeply ingrained in us.

595
00:38:41,140 --> 00:38:49,920
We talk about test-time compute scaling in AI as if throwing more computation at a problem linearly equates to better intelligence.

596
00:38:50,580 --> 00:39:00,440
But if a two-step solution is mathematically sound and a 10-step solution is just padded with repetitive filler, the 10-step solution isn't exhibiting deeper thought.

597
00:39:00,620 --> 00:39:02,600
It is exhibiting a proxy collapse.

598
00:39:02,700 --> 00:39:03,100
Exactly.

599
00:39:03,420 --> 00:39:07,900
We are financially rewarding the machine for faking hard work.

600
00:39:07,900 --> 00:39:16,100
So if the AI is essentially trapped in this hallucination where long equals correct because of its biased training diet, how do we fix it?

601
00:39:16,640 --> 00:39:20,400
My first instinct would be to just program a hard character limit.

602
00:39:20,740 --> 00:39:23,840
Like if it writes more than 200 words, you dock its reward score.

603
00:39:23,940 --> 00:39:25,560
You actively punish it for rambling.

604
00:39:25,560 --> 00:39:28,880
That is the intuitive, heavy-handed engineering solution.

605
00:39:29,120 --> 00:39:32,480
But Flyxion demonstrates mathematically why that approach fails.

606
00:39:32,700 --> 00:39:33,020
Why?

607
00:39:33,320 --> 00:39:42,100
If you simply punish the AI for long answers, you are suppressing the long solution region of its behavior, but you aren't actually expanding its knowledge of the short solution region.

608
00:39:42,400 --> 00:39:45,840
Because it still doesn't know how to be short and correct at the same time.

609
00:39:46,300 --> 00:39:48,600
You've just told it that everything it tries is wrong.

610
00:39:48,600 --> 00:39:52,760
It's like yelling at a dog for barking without teaching it the command for quiet.

611
00:39:53,280 --> 00:39:53,720
Exactly.

612
00:39:54,260 --> 00:39:58,800
A penalty provides no gradient, no pathway toward discovering the short answer.

613
00:39:59,400 --> 00:40:00,900
You are just blinding the model.

614
00:40:01,340 --> 00:40:03,940
So what is the actual structural fix?

615
00:40:04,240 --> 00:40:12,240
The elegant solution, which was tested in the shorter but not worse study cited in the paper, is incredibly counterintuitive to the tech industry.

616
00:40:12,440 --> 00:40:12,980
What is it?

617
00:40:12,980 --> 00:40:18,860
The fix is to swallow your pride and reintroduce the easy math problems back into the training data.

618
00:40:18,940 --> 00:40:22,900
The exact data the engineers threw in the trash because they thought it was useless.

619
00:40:23,100 --> 00:40:23,340
Yes.

620
00:40:23,340 --> 00:40:25,720
You feed the model simple arithmetic.

621
00:40:26,660 --> 00:40:30,920
Because on an easy problem, the AI doesn't need to ramble.

622
00:40:31,460 --> 00:40:39,360
It can effortlessly stumble into a short, highly efficient, two-word answer, achieve a 100% success rate, and get the maximum reward.

623
00:40:39,800 --> 00:40:42,740
And suddenly, the AI's entire worldview shatters.

624
00:40:42,980 --> 00:40:43,460
It does.

625
00:40:43,560 --> 00:40:47,160
It expands what geometric mathematicians call the fiber of correct solutions.

626
00:40:47,340 --> 00:40:49,260
Let's define fiber here so we don't lose anyone.

627
00:40:49,260 --> 00:40:55,440
Think of a fiber as a thick bundle of wires, where every wire represents a possible pathway to get the correct answer.

628
00:40:56,340 --> 00:41:03,180
Under the hard problems-only training regime, the engineers had essentially taken scissors and snipped all the short wires out of the bundle.

629
00:41:04,020 --> 00:41:09,720
The fiber collapsed so that only the incredibly long, convoluted wires remained intact.

630
00:41:09,720 --> 00:41:13,400
So the AI thought the long wires were the only way to conduct electricity.

631
00:41:13,640 --> 00:41:13,760
Right.

632
00:41:14,040 --> 00:41:18,840
By showing the AI easy problems, you are grafting the short wires back into the bundle.

633
00:41:19,240 --> 00:41:23,620
You repopulate the short trajectory region of that geometric fiber.

634
00:41:23,880 --> 00:41:29,180
You are finally proving to the AI that length and correctness are entirely orthogonal properties.

635
00:41:29,660 --> 00:41:31,240
They operate completely independently.

636
00:41:31,740 --> 00:41:32,780
You could be short and wrong.

637
00:41:32,860 --> 00:41:33,680
You can be short and right.

638
00:41:33,760 --> 00:41:36,160
You could be long and wrong or long and right.

639
00:41:36,160 --> 00:41:37,900
And this is the critical takeaway.

640
00:41:38,580 --> 00:41:40,460
Feeding it easy problems is not a penalty.

641
00:41:40,940 --> 00:41:42,620
It is a morphological repair.

642
00:41:42,620 --> 00:41:44,580
Just like the linguistic suffixes.

643
00:41:45,140 --> 00:41:45,400
Yes.

644
00:41:46,240 --> 00:41:49,040
It doesn't alter the ultimate goal of getting the right answer.

645
00:41:49,520 --> 00:41:52,920
It corrects the AI's internal representation of the universe.

646
00:41:52,920 --> 00:42:07,000
It demonstrates to the AI that a short solution is a perfectly admissible, valid way to exist in the world before the AI permanently internalizes the false belief that it must ramble to survive.

647
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:09,620
This is where everything clicks together for me.

648
00:42:09,740 --> 00:42:19,920
Because giving an AI an easy math problem so it learns the difference between long and correct is mechanically the exact same thing as a Spanish speaker choosing the verb ser over estar.

649
00:42:20,240 --> 00:42:23,400
It is the exact same underlying cognitive mechanism.

650
00:42:23,640 --> 00:42:26,800
They are both tools used to establish the true structure of reality.

651
00:42:27,340 --> 00:42:32,200
They are both separating the persistent, essential jawar from the accidental, noisy chorid.

652
00:42:32,260 --> 00:42:34,740
Which brings us to the grand unification of these three papers.

653
00:42:34,740 --> 00:42:35,820
So what does this all mean?

654
00:42:35,940 --> 00:42:37,380
We have to tie these threads together.

655
00:42:37,820 --> 00:42:47,040
How do English adjectives, surgical vocabulary in a Swahili hospital, and the training parameters of a Silicon Valley AI all reflect the exact same mathematical truth?

656
00:42:47,040 --> 00:42:53,140
To unify them, we have to look at how all complex systems grow and stabilize over time.

657
00:42:53,680 --> 00:42:59,040
The paper refers to this overarching dynamic as the incremental augmentation principle.

658
00:42:59,040 --> 00:43:06,660
And the most beautiful, tangible example of this actually comes from the first paper's analysis of the historical evolution of the Arabic script.

659
00:43:07,140 --> 00:43:11,680
Oh, walk us through that history, because the physical constraints of writing explain so much here.

660
00:43:12,240 --> 00:43:18,140
In the very early centuries of Islam, Arabic manuscripts were written in a skeletal script known as the Razm.

661
00:43:18,140 --> 00:43:26,500
And in this early, stripped-down script, many consonants that represented completely different phonetic sounds were graphically identical on the page.

662
00:43:26,580 --> 00:43:27,440
How identical?

663
00:43:27,720 --> 00:43:28,060
Completely.

664
00:43:28,440 --> 00:43:33,320
For example, the base shapes for the letters B, T, and The were just a simple, unadorned curve.

665
00:43:33,480 --> 00:43:34,520
They looked exactly the same.

666
00:43:34,740 --> 00:43:36,800
Which seems like an absolute nightmare for a reader.

667
00:43:36,940 --> 00:43:40,080
How did anyone decipher a sentence of three different letters look identical?

668
00:43:40,420 --> 00:43:43,080
They relied entirely on contextual confusability.

669
00:43:43,280 --> 00:43:45,480
Ah, just like the wooden tree example.

670
00:43:45,480 --> 00:43:53,120
If you are reading a text about farming and you see that curved letter, your brain uses the context to guess the word is wheat, not meat.

671
00:43:53,360 --> 00:43:53,920
Exactly.

672
00:43:54,560 --> 00:43:58,440
For early close-knit communities sharing oral traditions, context was enough.

673
00:43:59,140 --> 00:44:14,500
As the Islamic empire expanded massively, and the texts became highly complex detailed legal contracts, dense scientific treatises, precise theological texts relying purely on a reader's contextual guesswork became incredibly dangerous.

674
00:44:14,500 --> 00:44:16,760
The reachability divergence became too high.

675
00:44:16,860 --> 00:44:17,120
Yes.

676
00:44:17,600 --> 00:44:22,700
A misread consonant in a legal contract could transfer ownership of a farm to the wrong person.

677
00:44:23,240 --> 00:44:27,840
A misread letter in a medical text could prescribe the wrong herb and kill a patient.

678
00:44:28,300 --> 00:44:30,380
It was a leaming navigational collapse.

679
00:44:30,480 --> 00:44:33,400
So they were faced with a massive optimization problem.

680
00:44:33,580 --> 00:44:35,640
How do you fix this dangerous ambiguity?

681
00:44:35,640 --> 00:44:42,940
Because my modern instinct says, just throw away the broken alphabet and invent 30 completely new, totally distinct letters.

682
00:44:43,080 --> 00:44:46,340
But if they did that, they would destroy the cursive flow of the script.

683
00:44:46,840 --> 00:44:52,140
The skeletal rasm was already highly optimized for the motor efficiency of the human handwriting quickly with a reed pen.

684
00:44:52,680 --> 00:44:57,300
Inventing complex new shapes would increase the physical and cognitive cost of writing astronomically.

685
00:44:57,420 --> 00:45:02,000
Just like inventing a brand new word for the ARM instead of just adding a suffix.

686
00:45:02,260 --> 00:45:02,640
Exactly.

687
00:45:02,640 --> 00:45:04,600
So what was the morphological repair?

688
00:45:04,900 --> 00:45:05,480
What did they do?

689
00:45:05,760 --> 00:45:06,640
Systematic dotting.

690
00:45:06,920 --> 00:45:11,860
They kept the shared, efficient base shape, and they simply added tiny diacritical dots.

691
00:45:12,720 --> 00:45:14,640
A dot below the curve makes it a B.

692
00:45:15,040 --> 00:45:16,620
Two dots above makes it a T.

693
00:45:16,800 --> 00:45:18,520
Three dots above makes it a T.

694
00:45:18,820 --> 00:45:22,180
A microscopic physical intervention for a massive informational payoff?

695
00:45:22,460 --> 00:45:24,080
It is the ultimate morphological repair.

696
00:45:24,380 --> 00:45:26,120
You get a massive return on investment.

697
00:45:26,760 --> 00:45:31,440
The stable, cheap, symbolic substrate, the curve, supports low-cost refinements.

698
00:45:31,440 --> 00:45:33,140
The principle is clear.

699
00:45:33,820 --> 00:45:40,440
Put the high-value, identity-defining distinctions closest to the base and relegate the low-value annotations to the periphery.

700
00:45:40,660 --> 00:45:41,900
That is the adjective chart.

701
00:45:42,120 --> 00:45:44,360
It is the exact same geometry as the adjective chart.

702
00:45:44,760 --> 00:45:47,480
In English grammar, the noun is the stable base curve.

703
00:45:47,480 --> 00:45:55,300
The material adjective, wooden, is the crucial dot placed right next to it because it carries high informational leverage about the object's persistence.

704
00:45:56,380 --> 00:46:04,380
The opinion adjective, beautiful, is pushed far away because it's a low-value subjective annotation you can drop without losing your grip on reality.

705
00:46:04,380 --> 00:46:08,080
So the Arabic dots repair the dangerous ambiguity of the written script.

706
00:46:08,720 --> 00:46:15,180
The English adjective order repairs the ambiguity of physical objects by pulling the physical reality closest to the noun?

707
00:46:15,680 --> 00:46:16,020
Yes.

708
00:46:16,280 --> 00:46:24,560
Scientific jargon, like adding a suffix to separate hand from arm, repairs the danger of colexification routing a patient to the wrong surgery.

709
00:46:24,980 --> 00:46:32,660
And feeding easy math problems to an AI repairs its collapsed neural fiber by separating the accident of length from the substance of truth.

710
00:46:32,660 --> 00:46:35,080
They are all identical phenomena.

711
00:46:35,540 --> 00:46:42,280
They are convergent evolutionary solutions across different substrates to solve the exact same constraint satisfaction problem.

712
00:46:42,400 --> 00:46:44,060
It's all just the architecture of distinctions.

713
00:46:44,300 --> 00:46:48,640
And that brings us to the ultimate paradigm-shifting conclusion of Flickshien's research.

714
00:46:49,180 --> 00:47:00,960
The true measure of an intelligent system, whether you are evaluating a human child, a sprawling ancient culture, a linguistic grammar, or a trillion-parameter machine, is not its ability to reduce uncertainty.

715
00:47:01,200 --> 00:47:01,460
Right.

716
00:47:01,460 --> 00:47:08,280
Intelligence is not the ability to compress data into the smallest file size or communicate as quickly and predictably as possible.

717
00:47:08,720 --> 00:47:13,040
The true measure of intelligence is its ability to preserve the distinctions that matter.

718
00:47:13,520 --> 00:47:18,560
To keep the community's future open, flexible, and strictly navigable.

719
